<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANATOMY LESSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Steve Weinstein's July 29 article on Mark Frost, co-creator of television's 
"Twin Peaks," Frost is quoted as describing a character as a "walking 
cerebellum," when he should have called him a "walking cerebrum." 
</P>
<P>
The cerebrum, location of the cerebral cortex, is the major part of the brain 
and controls thought and other intellectual processes. The cerebellum, in 
contrast, is a smaller section that helps maintain coordination and facilitates 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
In Charles Champlin's "Spike Lee Gets Personal," Lee mentioned the athlete who 
tears a rotator "cup" when he meant to say the rotator "cuff," tissue 
surrounding the shoulder joint consisting of muscle and tendons. 
</P>
<P>
Proper labeling of body parts makes for better filmmaking! 
</P>
<P>
DAVID E. AFTERGOOD, MD 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
