<HEADLINE>
<P>
LATINO STEREOTYPES AND THE DRIVE FOR EXCELLENCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As I finished reading Sean Mitchell's article on Luis Valdez, a thought flashed 
through my mind: Would Valdez have come so far and done so much if he had not 
faced the obstacle of the "Latino" tag? (By this I mean "obstacle" from the 
Anglo point of view.) 
</P>
<P>
I'm speaking of the extra incentive one feels when he or she strives to do 
better than the Anglo kid with the symbolic silver spoon in his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
I feel sorry for those who were not born with a fire inside that, angled just 
right, can grow into a unique creative inferno. 
</P>
<P>
I'm so proud of my Latino brothers and sisters who commit themselves to 
projects beyond being the toughest one in the gang. Viva to us -- we're much 
better than people think we are; but most important, we're much better than 
what we ourselves have thought we were! 
</P>
<P>
HELEN M. ROMAN 
</P>
<P>
Hacienda Heights 
</P>
