<DOCNO> LA080590-0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257203 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 5, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 5; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
757 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN RIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
FRUITS OF THE NEW AGE OF DISARMAMENT; 
</P>
<P>
IRAQ IS ONLY THE START. THIS SHOULD WAKE US TO THE DANGER OF UNCONSIDERED 
DEFENSE CUTS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK J. BUCHANAN, Patrick J. Buchanan writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Just as Japan's move into Manchuria in 1931 was a wake-up call to the West, 
heralding what was ahead for the new decade, so the Iraqi drive into Kuwait is 
a harbinger of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
With his blitzkrieg invasion of oil-rich Kuwait, Saddam Hussein has introduced 
us to the new realities of the Near East. The Carter Doctrine, whereby the 
United States vowed to resist with force any effort by a hostile power to take 
over the Persian Gulf, is dead. If you wish to survive in this region, Hussein 
has telegraphed his Arab neighbors, you will answer to Baghdad, not Washington. 
The United States is no longer policeman of the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
Short of blockading Iraqi ports, an act of war, the U.S. cannot force Hussein 
to cough up the tiny country he has just swallowed. As no vital U.S. interest 
is at stake, we aren't going to do that. An America that packed up and 
abandoned Lebanon after 250 Marines were lost in a single explosion is not 
going to send the 82nd Airborne up the Euphrates valley to avenge Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
Saddam Hussein gambled that the Rapid Deployment Force and Sixth Fleet were, by 
and large, a superpower bluff. His gamble paid off. Doesn't look very much like 
the end of history, does it? 
</P>
<P>
This display of Iraqi military power came just 24 hours after House Armed 
Services had shredded the U.S. defense budget, voting to kill the B-2 Stealth 
bomber, gut the Strategic Defense Initiative and cut U.S. armed forces by 
129,000 men -- a $24-billion chop. 
</P>
<P>
We are headed for a new disarmament decade; and we had best prepare for more 
mornings like Thursday last. 
</P>
<P>
Clearly, 1990 is not 1960. Even after the Reagan buildup, U.S. armed forces and 
battle fleets, first-rate though they are, are still only half the size they 
were when John F. Kennedy held office. Our missile force is inferior to the 
Soviets' and growing more so every month, as Moscow modernizes first-strike 
SS-18 missiles and builds hundreds of new second-strike SS-24 and SS-25 mobile 
missiles. 
</P>
<P>
There are a half-dozen regional powers, deeply hostile to U.S. interests, which 
were inconsequential in 1960. Among them are North Korea, Vietnam, Iran, Iraq, 
Syria, Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
Yet, as America's relative power diminishes, U.S. overseas commitments are 
still expanding. We are committed to go to war on behalf of 15 NATO allies and 
our red line has been moved east to the Oder and Neisse Rivers. We just signed 
a pact with Greece to come to its aid in the event of war with Turkey. We have 
a commitment to Israel that brought us to the brink of nuclear war in 1973. In 
the Persian Gulf, until last week, we had the Carter Doctrine. And we still 
have pacts with South Korea, Japan, the Philippines, Australia and New Zealand, 
and the Organization of American States. 
</P>
<P>
And, as new commitments are taken on and the old ones call for more U.S. power 
to sustain them, we have begun closing bases, drawing down troop levels, 
eliminating weapons. If this continues, the United States is headed for 
foreign-policy bankruptcy and eventual war. 
</P>
<P>
It is time that Bush informed Congress that if it is going to eliminate forces, 
he is going to start terminating commitments. 
</P>
<P>
The congressional assault on the defense budget has taken on an almost mindless 
character. Programs cut, like SDI and Stealth, are 21st-Century weapons of 
defense and deterrence, while the armor, which Congress spared, is designed to 
help win World War II in Europe. We are eliminating new planes needed to strike 
and punish potential enemies, while keeping open army bases strategically 
located to protect us from the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
The President needs to make some hard choices, and he needs to inform the world 
of the consequences of those choices. If we are going to cut back on the Army, 
Navy and Air Force, we have to begin sending word to nations like Kuwait that 
depended on us, like Kuwait, that they are on their own, so they can begin 
making a separate peace with the Saddam Husseins of the new world. How long can 
the United States continue spending more for the defense of Europe than 
Europeans? How long should we defend the oil lifeline of Europe and Japan, with 
no support from the navies of Europe and Japan? 
</P>
<P>
If America's armed forces are to be cut, they should be cut with an eye to 
defending the American nation and people first. Missile defense is the highest 
priority, followed by the air and naval capacity to defend our continent, 
coasts and sea lanes, and to retaliate against an enemy aggressor. 
Unsurprisingly, this is where the chowderheads of Capitol Hill first decided to 
cut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080590-0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257204 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 5, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 2; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
582 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA COMMENTARY; 
</P>
<P>
THE BUDGET-BUSTERS REGROUP; 
</P>
<P>
WIELDING THE POWER OF PROPOSITION 98, THE SCHOOLS WON THEIR SHARE -- A LESSON 
NOT LOST ON THE LOSERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOEL FOX, Joel Fox is president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Assn. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The battle for the 1991 California budget is over, and the only contender left 
standing in the middle of the ring is education. It's not unscathed -- there's 
a bit of blood dripping from its nose -- but it's standing, and none of the 
other interests that sought shares of the state budget can say that. 
</P>
<P>
Of course, it wasn't a fair fight. Unlike the other combatants, education went 
into the ring with a shield. In a bare-knuckle fight, the one who gets to bring 
a shield usually wins. 
</P>
<P>
Education's shield was Proposition 98, an initiative that was barely passed by 
the electorate in 1988, which guaranteed primary, secondary and community 
college education 40%-plus of the state general fund budget. With that 
protection, education added $1.8 billion to its $17.8-billion budget, an 
increase of 10%. The state budget as a whole increased a smaller 7.6%. 
</P>
<P>
Just about every other agency in the state budget was a loser. 
</P>
<P>
The losers may be down, but they're not unconscious. They know why they lost 
and education won. They know about the shield -- and they each want one of 
their own. 
</P>
<P>
Among the losers is health-care funding. Health care makes up less than 15% of 
the state budget, down about 4% or 5% from a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
The health-care industry may put up a number of initiatives to protect spending 
on doctors, hospitals and nursing homes. If health took about 20% of the state 
budget a few years ago, it will want to secure 25% now -- just to be on the 
safe side. There are more Californians now, so it figures there are more sick 
ones in need of care. Taking a page from education's notebook, health's 
protected share of the budget probably will have an escalator clause to take an 
even greater share in each passing year. 
</P>
<P>
Welfare will want to protect its share of the budget, and if health care can 
take 25% of the general funds, then so can welfare. 
</P>
<P>
Prisons have been doing quite well under the Deukmejian administration, but the 
governor is ready to hang up his keys. With the Iron Duke no longer available 
to look out for prison interests, they'll need protection of their own. Ten 
percent doesn't seem too much to ask as a guaranteed share of the budget. We're 
talking about public safety. 
</P>
<P>
Local government has been knocked around in the budget battle so many times 
before, it came to this fight a little punchy. The wobbly legs are from years 
of trekking to Sacramento to beg for a share of the budget to fund programs 
imposed by the state to be administered and paid for by the locals. A guarantee 
seems just the tonic to put some spring back in local government's step. 
Fifteen percent seems fair. Twenty percent seems more fair. 
</P>
<P>
And so it will go. Each dependency of the state will place an initiative on the 
ballot to secure protection for itself. When all have armor, there won't be a 
need for budget battles. 
</P>
<P>
Of course, after each agency wins by initiative what it feels is its fair 
share, the guarantees will add up to 175% of the funds available. Isn't it 
impossible to spend 75% more than what you can pay for? Not at all. With the 
cost-of-living escalators currently built into the system outstripping 
available revenue, that's what we regularly get now -- a budget bigger than we 
can afford. 
</P>
<P>
There will be one place where we can cut and save money: the Legislature 
itself. If all these initiatives pass and all the money in the budget is 
automatically designated, we can go back to having a part-time Legislature. A 
one-hour session sounds about right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
