<HEADLINE>
<P>
MALATHION BLAMED FOR RESPIRATORY PROBLEMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kathleen Doheny's column "Your Body: It's a Mean Season for Breathing" 
describes an increase in coughs and upper respiratory problems this summer. 
Apparently, no one has determined the cause of this increase. 
</P>
<P>
What environmental conditions are different this summer, as compared to 
previous summers? The first thing that comes to mind is the state's incessant 
aerial spraying of malathion and sugary bait. Although we were assured at one 
time that malathion would not hurt us, the state has so far exceeded its 
liberal standards for safety by continuing the sprayings beyond original 
deadlines. 
</P>
<P>
Is there a correlation between the sprayings and the increase in respiratory 
infections (which include pneumonia)? Is the aerial spraying one of the factors 
contributing to these infections? 
</P>
<P>
PAMELA FORD 
</P>
<P>
Redlands 
</P>
</TEXT>
