<HEADLINE>
<P>
'BLACK DRAGON' -- SECRETIVE ASIAN GANG TRACES TO ALIENATED VIET REFUGEES OF 
'70S; 
</P>
<P>
CRIME: SOME WERE PUNKS. SOME WERE TORN BETWEEN CULTURES. POLICE SAY THEIR 
ACTIVITIES HAVE MOVED BEYOND PETTY THEFT TO EXTORTION, BURGLARIES AND 
ROBBERIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JESSE KATZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Back in the early 1980s, when Southeast Asian gangs were still in their 
infancy, Los Angeles Police Department Detective William Park remembers 
street-wise Vietnamese boys taunting, "New Wave never ends." 
</P>
<P>
It was partly a reference to their rebellious look: long spiked hair, baggy 
black pants and white shirts buttoned to the collar. 
</P>
<P>
But it was also a macho slogan, Park believed, meant to say that the tough 
refugee youths and their secretive, loosely knit alliances would not be easily 
quashed. 
</P>
<P>
"It was like they were saying . . . you couldn't take them down," recalled 
Park, an investigator in the Police Department's Asian Crimes Section. "You put 
them away, but there's always going to be younger blood taking their place. It 
never ends." 
</P>
<P>
Nearly a decade later, it hasn't. Police say those same teen-agers grew up to 
be the core of a gang known today as "Black Dragon," a group of mostly ethnic 
Chinese refugees from Vietnam who are thought to be responsible for dozens of 
armed robberies in Asian communities throughout the San Gabriel Valley. 
</P>
<P>
On July 24, after months of surveillance, police arrested 18 suspected members 
of the gang, whose total membership may range from 40 to 100, according to 
various law enforcement estimates. 
</P>
<P>
Because many of their alleged victims have been reluctant to come forward, 
however, 13 of the suspects had to be released for lack of evidence, officers 
said. Of the five who remain in custody -- each in lieu of $300,000 bail -- 
four were charged with robbery and kidnaping in connection with a heist at a 
San Gabriel beauty parlor. The fifth was charged in connection with a similar 
holdup at a salon near Chinatown. 
</P>
<P>
In a press conference after the arrests, Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman 
Block asked for the Asian community's help in identifying the suspects and 
tying them to more crimes. He said gangs such as Black Dragon prey on 
immigrants' fears of retaliation, their unfamiliarity with the U.S. legal 
system and a tendency to write off such assaults as merely bad luck. 
</P>
<P>
"The Asian victim is least likely to come forward and report their 
victimization," said Block, whose department teamed up with six other police 
agencies to make the arrests. "That's the kind of thing we're trying to break 
through." 
</P>
<P>
But leaders in the San Gabriel Valley's Asian communities said last week that 
cooperation with police will come only after a long educational process, 
including frequent patrols, neighborhood meetings and the hiring of more 
officers who speak some of their 42 dialects. 
</P>
<P>
"I always encourage people to cooperate with police, but many are afraid of 
revenge," said David Ma, who runs an immigration law and consulting firm in 
Monterey Park. "They're skeptical that the police can protect them. They think, 
if the police can protect them, then why are there so many of these robberies 
happening?" 
</P>
<P>
According to police and probation officers, the early members of Black Dragon 
came to this country in the late 1970s as junior high school students -- poor 
teen-agers who spent their free time stealing car stereos in the neighborhoods 
north of Chinatown. 
</P>
<P>
Like other Southeast Asian gangs, their alliances were fluid. Three or four of 
them might meet one day at a pool hall or over a hot bowl of the traditional 
Vietnamese soup, Pho, and agree to join forces in a burglary or auto theft, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
Some displayed cigarette burns on their wrists -- supposed symbols of their 
immunity to pain -- while others wore tattoos bearing the images of tigers, 
eagles and dragons. "They were just street-level punks," Park said. 
</P>
<P>
Some of them were also probably lost, confused young men torn between two 
cultures, say mental-health experts and school officials who have worked with 
Southeast Asian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
Such gang members, they said, arrive here in their early teens, their 
educations disrupted, their families fragmented, and their aspirations replaced 
by feelings of rootlessness and alienation. 
</P>
<P>
At home, the youths speak Cantonese or Vietnamese with their parents, many of 
whom are former farmers or fishermen with often conservative and restrictive 
ideas of how their children should behave. Out on the streets, they encounter 
an English-speaking world that glorifies power and material wealth. 
</P>
<P>
"They want very much to be like American kids," said May To, program 
coordinator at the Asian Youth Center in Monterey Park. "But that usually means 
money to go to a dance or out for a drink -- money that their parents don't 
have, or if they do, they won't allow them to use in those ways." 
</P>
<P>
Unprepared for those conflicts, some of the most disaffected take their chances 
with crime, psychologists and social workers say. As the members of Black 
Dragon reached their 20s, however, they gradually developed into what police 
now consider one of the largest and most active Asian gangs in the San Gabriel 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
Petty theft gave way to extortion, commercial burglary and home-invasion 
robberies, officers say. Victims were routinely bound with duct tape, 
electrical cords and clothes hangers. The uncooperative were beaten, 
pistol-whipped and tortured. 
</P>
<P>
"They became very organized and very dangerous," said Christopher Kuk, a 
probation officer in the county's Asian Gang Unit. "If they see you as a threat 
to their well-being, they will not hesitate to remove you from the face of this 
earth." 
</P>
<P>
Their name is not well-known in the immigrant communities of Alhambra, San 
Gabriel or Monterey Park, largely because they operate furtively and do not 
promote the indentity of the gang, police say. Often, they will skip town to 
commit crimes in other cities with sizable Vietnamese populations, such as 
Boston, Houston, San Jose and Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
A couple of years ago, recalled Steve Kornfeld, dean of students at San Gabriel 
High School, a young Vietnamese student approached him and pointed to 
Kornfeld's aging Seiko wristwatch. 
</P>
<P>
"Your watch is no good," the boy said, flashing a fancy gold timepiece that 
Kornfeld figured cost more than $1,500. When Kornfeld asked the youth where he 
got his watch, he remembers him saying, "You get on a plane, go away two days 
and come back and you have a nice watch. It's easy." 
</P>
<P>
Before the arrests last month, sheriff's deputies, assisted by officers from 
Los Angeles, Pasadena, Monterey Park, El Monte, Arcadia and Baldwin Park, had 
been staking out the Black Dragon "crash pad" on a dead-end street in Rosemead. 
</P>
<P>
From there, police say they followed Thuan Kso Ngo, 29, Anthony Lenh, 19, Ty 
Pham, 22, and Vang Tran, 23, to the Beauty of Paris Salon in San Gabriel. Five 
hairstylists were in the shop, along with four customers, when the men 
allegedly barged in, two of them waving pistols. 
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old the owner of the salon remembers being ordered to lie face-down 
on the floor, as the men stripped the women of their jewelry and snatched more 
than $1,000 from the register. 
</P>
<P>
"We were scared," the owner said. "I kept thinking about God, that God would 
help us." 
</P>
<P>
Officers waiting outside arrested the four men as soon as they exited. At the 
dumpy, one-story bungalow in Rosemead where police said members of the gang had 
been living for the summer, officers arrested 14 others, including Hong Ly, 21, 
suspected in the Chinatown robbery. 
</P>
<P>
Of the 13 who were later released, five were women. Four of those arrested were 
juveniles. All were photographed and fingerprinted. 
</P>
<P>
A public defender for one of the suspected gang members did not respond to a 
request for comment. It could not be determined whether the others had 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, back at the alleged crash pad last week, a middle-aged man cleaned 
up a pile of beer cans from the Alanreed Avenue property. 
</P>
<P>
"This was just a place where young people could come hang out," said the man, 
who identified himself as the building's owner. "It was all summer-vacation 
fun." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Police say this house on Alanreed Avenue in Rosemead was a Black Dragon 
"crash pad." Fourteen people were arrested there in a July raid. LOU MACK / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080590-0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257263 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 5, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 1; Column 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Down to Earth: At Eisenhower Park in Monrovia, Michael Daniel Pokrajac, 
6, looks down from the top level of his "rocket." KAREN TAPIA / Los Angeles 
Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080590-0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257264 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 5, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 1; Column 5 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1052 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUTS MAY CRIPPLE SOME SOCIAL SERVICE PROGRAMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VICKI TORRES, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley agencies could lose up to $13 million in mental health care 
and children's services money under state budget cuts imposed last week by Gov. 
George Deukmejian, social service providers say. 
</P>
<P>
Among the programs cut by Deukmejian is a YWCA-run child abuse prevention 
program that has counseled 14,000 schoolchildren annually in South Pasadena, 
Pasadena and San Marino for the past five years. 
</P>
<P>
The Covina office of the County Department of Children's Services and the 
county-run Arcadia Mental Health Clinic, whose services were significantly 
reduced last year, also face cuts when the County Board of Supervisors meets 
this week to pass along the state cuts in the county's budget. 
</P>
<P>
At least five nonprofit mental health care agencies also face county pass-along 
cuts, including three of the largest: Foothill Community Mental Health in 
Glendora, La Puente Valley Mental Health Center in La Puente and Pacific 
Clinics, which operates in four San Gabriel Valley cities. 
</P>
<P>
The budget reductions mean that abused children, isolated and depressed seniors 
and the homeless mentally ill will have nowhere to turn for help, said Susan 
Mandel, president of Pacific Clinics. "Some of those folks are just going to 
plain die," she said. 
</P>
<P>
"What's going to be left in this stripped down system is people in hospitals or 
crisis management centers," said Ted Meyers, director of Foothill Community 
Mental Health. "Unless (the supervisors) make a change in direction, they're 
going to cut outpatient mental health care. I'll be surprised if we'll be here 
in two months." 
</P>
<P>
Agencies throughout the state are reeling under cuts in four separate 
categories that Deukmejian blue-penciled into a $55.7-billion state budget 
signed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
For Los Angeles County, those cuts amount to $10.1 million in child abuse 
prevention funds from the state Child Abuse Prevention Training Act, $21.3 
million in mental health funds, $12 million in juvenile justice program money 
and $11 million in child welfare services. 
</P>
<P>
In the San Gabriel Valley, those cuts make up the bulk of money provided for 
children's mental health services contracted out to various nonprofit agencies, 
said Deborah Hamilton, San Gabriel Valley regional director of the Mental 
Health Assn. 
</P>
<P>
"There are more children out in the bedroom communities than in downtown Los 
Angeles," Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
Francis Dowling, assistant chief of the county Department of Mental Health, 
said cuts are expected this week in the budgets of virtually all agencies, with 
reductions in funding ranging from 10% to 100%. 
</P>
<P>
For Casitas Pacificas, an El Monte residential care center for 36 mentally ill 
patients, the cuts could mean the closing of the 9-year-old home and of a 
Baldwin Park vocational training school attended by many of its patients, said 
Richard Guajardo, executive director. 
</P>
<P>
Guajardo said he is trying to find agencies or homes to refer his clients to in 
anticipation of the budget cuts, but many of the alternatives also face cuts. 
"There just doesn't seem to be any place to refer them," he said. "I don't know 
what we're going to do." 
</P>
<P>
Mandel said many agencies are hoping for a legislative override of the 
governor's actions. Otherwise, she said, many of the patients being seen by the 
various agencies will turn to the streets. "There's no place for these people 
to go," she said. "It's not like they can go down the street to a private 
doctor." 
</P>
<P>
Many of the patients are indigent, with long histories of stays in state mental 
hospitals, Mandel said. They are severely mentally ill with schizophrenia or 
manic-depressive disorders and need supervision and drugs to maintain 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
"They are the kind of folks that if they don't get their medication, they hear 
voices telling them they are worthless and to kill themselves," Mandel said. 
</P>
<P>
She added that the governor's actions appear to be withdrawing the state from 
mental health care, a state government responsibility since the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
Although many of the agencies are nonprofit with other funding, Meyers said 
that nonprofits cannot operate without a base of government funding. 
</P>
<P>
Whereas some San Gabriel agencies are waiting to see how much they will be cut 
by the county supervisors, operators of the child abuse prevention program run 
by the YWCA Pasadena Foothill Valley branch already know they won't be getting 
any money. 
</P>
<P>
The program was funded directly by the state, said community outreach 
coordinator Norma Navarro. Children from 4 to 18 were counseled to prevent 
physical, emotional and sexual abuse, as well as neglect and abduction. 
</P>
<P>
The program was probably cut because no statistics exist to prove its 
effectiveness, Navarro said. 
</P>
<P>
"Some intervention programs were funded, but that occurs after the fact, after 
the child has been abused," Navarro said. "Prevention is the key."TARGETS OF 
BUDGET CUTS 
</P>
<P>
Some San Gabriel Valley agencies facing funding cuts: 
</P>
<P>
* Casitas Pacificas, El Monte, provides housing and counseling for 36 mentally 
ill patients with $406,089 annually in state mental health funds. 
</P>
<P>
* Foothill Community Mental Health, Glendora, provides outpatient counseling to 
1,000 mentally ill clients, from children to seniors, with $560,000 in state 
mental health money. 
</P>
<P>
* Inter Community Alternative Network (ICAN), Pasadena, maintains a caseload of 
95 chronically mentally ill patients weekly with $360,000 in state mental 
health funds. 
</P>
<P>
* La Puente Valley Mental Health Center, La Puente, provides outpatient 
counseling to 1,500 chronically mentally ill patients annually with about $1.5 
million in state mental health funds. 
</P>
<P>
* Los Angeles County Department of Children's Services, Covina, provides 
counseling and evaluation services for about 8,000 children annually. 
</P>
<P>
* Pacific Clinics in Pasadena, Duarte, Rosemead and Irwindale, counsel 2,000 
abused children, senior citizens and mentally ill adults each year with $4 
million annually in state mental health funds. 
</P>
<P>
* Structured Transitional Employment Programs (STEP), Baldwin Park, provides 
job training for 55 mentally ill clients annually with $178,356 in state mental 
health funds. 
</P>
<P>
* YWCA Pasadena-Foothill Valley, Pasadena, presents child abuse awareness and 
prevention programs to 14,000 schoolchildren annually in Pasadena, South 
Pasadena and San Marino with $70,000 in state funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
