<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOTNOTE FOOTNOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his perceptive April 8 review of "The Cinema of Adventure, Romance and 
Terror," David Colker mentions that "some of the behind-the-scenes anecdotes . 
. . are suspect because the book is not footnoted and the sources . . . go 
mostly unnamed." 
</P>
<P>
Most of the material in my book is from primary sources, such as author 
conversations and interviews over a period of many years with personnel 
involved in production of the films and from information in studio files. . . . 
</P>
<P>
For example, our information on "The Most Dangerous Game" was obtained from the 
producer, the director, the music supervisor, four of the cameramen, two 
effects technicians, the first matte artist, a stuntman, two lead players and 
the RKO production files. 
</P>
<P>
We tried to avoid published sources and whatever secondary materials were used 
are attributed in the text. Further blame may be attached to the editor's 
college-days hatred of reading footnotes. 
</P>
<P>
GEORGE E. TURNER 
</P>
<P>
HOLLYWOOD 
</P>
</TEXT>
