<HEADLINE>
<P>
PICTURE IN ERROR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The picture you ran accompanying your story on the Jackson Drive connection to 
Route 52 ("Jackson Drive Extension Stirs Debate," July 14) is totally 
inaccurate. That valley is precisely where the road is not going. 
</P>
<P>
Jackson Drive winds its way through the far western edge of the park, out of 
sight and sound of this valley. 
</P>
<P>
The valley shown is designated for overnight camping, family and group 
picnicking. According to the master plan, Jackson Drive will provide access for 
those unable to hike into this area, "currently the most inaccessible, and to 
many people, unknown area of the park." 
</P>
<P>
Jackson Drive has been in the park's master plan and the city's traffic 
circulation plan since 1960. The project was listed as one of the 12 local road 
projects that would be funded if Proposition A, the half-cent sales tax measure 
passed. Proposition A did pass, and the people expect those projects to be 
built ASAP. 
</P>
<P>
Subsequent votes by the City Council listed Jackson Drive as a state 
matching-funds project. The council also voted to accelerate the project so 
that Caltrans will build the interchange with California 52. 
</P>
<P>
Now there are those who say that Mission Trails Regional Park is a preserve, 
not a park with active recreational uses. In fact, it is both, responding to 
"the public's increasing need for 'close-in' park opportunities by providing 
varied wilderness, interpretive and active recreational facilities." (Master 
Plan, 1985). 
</P>
<P>
Thus, because Jackson Drive will advance the park concept and relieve traffic 
congestion on I-8, I-15 and our residential streets, and because it was 
approved by the people with Proposition A, this critical connection to 
California 52 must be built without delay. 
</P>
<P>
JUDY McCARTY 
</P>
<P>
San Diego City Council 
</P>
<P>
District 7 
</P>
<P>
Editor's Note: The Times mistakenly ran a file photograph of another area of 
the park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
