<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MOBIL AMENDS BALLOT FINANCIAL REPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mobil Oil Corp. has filed an amended financial report for the campaign 
committee that helped defeat a March ballot measure aimed at banning the use of 
hydrofluoric acid at the company's Torrance refinery. 
</P>
<P>
The new report, received Thursday by the Torrance city clerk, corrected a 
discrepancy in an earlier report that was caused by a mathematical error, said 
Charles H. Bell Jr., a Sacramento attorney representing Mobil. 
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the Mobil Oil Corp. Refinery Safety Committee/No on 
Measure A collected a total of $710,238.78, all but $200 of it from Mobil. The 
committee received $644,895.07 in monetary contributions from Mobil and 
$65,343.71 in "non-monetary contributions," which Bell described as staff time 
of Mobil employees. 
</P>
<P>
The only contributors besides Mobil were David E. Novitski, a Mobil attorney 
and the committee's treasurer, who gave $100, and attorney Ernest J. Getto, who 
also gave $100, the report says. 
</P>
<P>
The group spent $644,895.07, primarily on broadcast advertising, literature and 
polling, the report states. It reports no cash on hand as of June 30, the end 
of the reporting period. 
</P>
<P>
The ballot measure lost 3-1 in the March 6 Torrance election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
