<HEADLINE>
<P>
MONEY TALK / CARLA LAZZARESCHI: REVERSE MORTGAGE TURNS HOME EQUITY INTO CASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLA LAZZARESCHI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q: I recently heard of something called a reverse mortgage. I own my home free 
and clear and believe it is worth about $400,000. I am on a fixed income and 
would like to tap into my equity so I can have more money. I am an 82-year-old 
widow and live alone. I checked with three bankers in Southern California and 
all told me no reverse mortgage program was available in the state. Is this 
true? -- M.B.". 
</P>
<P>
A: No. But it's not surprising that you've had difficulty getting the full 
story on these complex and sometimes controversial mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
Reverse annuity mortgages were first offered in California in 1980 to help 
senior citizens who have substantial equities in their homes but need more cash 
to meet their living expenses. Basically, these mortgages allow owners who owe 
little or nothing on their home mortgages to tap into their equity without 
selling their homes. 
</P>
<P>
Here's how they work: Typically, a lending institution makes the homeowner a 
loan based on the borrower's age -- the minimum ranges from 62 to 65 -- and the 
property's appraised value. After taking its loan fees and points, the 
institution pays the homeowner the balance of the loan either in equal monthly 
installments, in a lump sum or as a line of credit for as long as the borrower 
continues living in the home. The loan balance -- actually the amount dispersed 
plus interest and loan fees -- is repaid when the house is sold by the owner or 
his heirs. 
</P>
<P>
These open-ended loans are complicated because it's impossible to know how long 
the homeowner will continue to live in the house. If he stays just a brief 
time, the reverse mortgage proves a costly way to pull equity out of the house 
because loan fees and points on the full potential loan amount are assessed at 
the outset. However, if he stays a very long time, the lending institution 
stands to pay out more than the home may be worth. Because of the risk, several 
institutions offering reverse mortgages charge an additional "guaranty fee" or 
require that they share in the appreciation of the home's value during the 
course of the loan. 
</P>
<P>
According to the American Assn. of Retired Persons, three private lenders offer 
reverse mortgages to Californians. They are: American Homestead in New Jersey, 
(800) 233-4762; Providential Home Income Plan in San Francisco, (800) 441-4428, 
and Capital Holding Corp. in Kentucky, (800) 942-6550. 
</P>
<P>
Each lender offers a slightly different loan package, explains Bronwyn Belling, 
a housing specialist at the AARP, so it is important for borrowers to carefully 
evaluate their choices before making a decision. 
</P>
<P>
Belling said that with a $200,000 loan at current interest rates, monthly 
payments from the three lenders mentioned previously would range from $903 to 
$1,124, with substantially varying requirements and restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
For more information about reverse mortgages, send a self-addressed, stamped 
envelop to the Independent Living Resource Center, 70 10th St., San Francisco, 
Calif. 94103. Another source is the American Assn. of Retired Persons. Send a 
postcard asking for Home-Made Money to AARP Fulfillment D-12894, 1909 K St. 
N.W., Washington, D.C. 20049. Delivery takes six to eight weeks. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Social Security Taxes Just Keep on Coming 
</P>
<P>
-: It's already August, and I'm still paying Social Security taxes. How much do 
I have to earn before I satisfy my obligation? It seems as though I finished 
paying the tax earlier last year. -- M.J. 
</P>
<P>
A: You didn't imagine it; you did finish paying your Social Security taxes 
earlier last year. This year, the Social Security tax rate and the maximum 
earnings subject to the tax were increased. 
</P>
<P>
The tax rate paid by employees, as well as their employers, this year is 7.65%, 
up from 7.51% in 1989. This year the rate is applied to the first $51,300 of 
earnings, for a maximum Social Security tax obligation of $3,924.45. Last year, 
the tax rate was applied to the first $48,000 of earnings, and the maximum 
amount of taxes paid by employees was $3,604.80. 
</P>
<P>
For 1991, the tax rate remains at 7.65%, but the amount of earnings subject to 
the tax has not yet been set. The level is established annually by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Both Spouses Can Reap Tax Break After Split 
</P>
<P>
-: My wife and I are getting a divorce. One of us will keep the house, and the 
other will buy another place in which to live. Is there any way we can both 
keep the $125,000 tax exclusion for home sale profits? -- I.C.". 
</P>
<P>
A: Yes; assuming that each of you is individually qualified to take advantage 
of the tax break, each may leave the marriage with a full $125,000 exemption. 
</P>
<P>
Under the tax laws, an individual or a married couple may exclude from taxation 
$125,000 of profits from the sale of their home if certain conditions are met. 
In the case of couples, at least one must be age 55 or more, and both must have 
owned and lived in the home for three of the past five years. Individuals must 
meet all three qualifications on their own, and once divorced, each former 
spouse must meet those three requirements to take the tax break. 
</P>
<P>
A caveat: Be sure that your divorce is completely final before selling the 
house you shared. If you are still married when you sell, you qualify for only 
a single $125,000 exemption that you would both be required to share, even if 
you file separate tax returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
