<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Louis Willie, the first black to join Shoal Creek Country Club, site of this 
week's PGA Championship, was relaxed during his initial visit as a member, his 
wife said. 
</P>
<P>
"He loved it," Yvonne Willie said of her husband's visit to Shoal Creek in 
Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
It wasn't Willie's first trip to the club, though. He was a spectator at the 
1984 PGA Championship at Shoal Creek. 
</P>
<P>
Willie, 66, an insurance executive, took a few strokes on the putting green 
Friday, three days after he received an honorary membership as part of an 
agreement that led civil rights groups to call off plans for picketing the 
previously all-white club during the PGA. 
</P>
<P>
It has been 25 years since he played golf. He wasn't able to get in a round 
because the course is closed as it gets some final touches in advance of 
Monday's opening practice round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
