<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. PROMINENCE IN WORLD AGRICULTURE MARKET EBBING; 
</P>
<P>
TRADE: IN THE GLOBAL FOOD ARENA, EXPERTS SAY, THE COUNTRY HAS LOST ITS CORNER 
ON TECHNOLOGY AND KNOWLEDGE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN KUSMER, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
INDIANAPOLIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Technology has been a major reason for the United States' success in the world 
agriculture market, but this country risks losing its prominence, experts said 
recently at a conference. 
</P>
<P>
"The day has passed when American agriculture had a lock on the world 
marketplace for food," U.S. Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter said. 
</P>
<P>
He joined international food experts, scholars and businessmen in Indianapolis 
recently to discuss global food trends during the 1990s at a conference 
sponsored by the conservative think tank Hudson Institute. 
</P>
<P>
The United States held 35% of the value of world trade in bulk agriculture 
commodities in 1988, Yeutter said, but in intermediate products such as flours 
and vegetable fats, the U.S. share dropped to 18%. Among consumer-oriented 
agriculture products, such as processed fruits, cut flowers and bakery 
products, American farmers have less than a 6% stake. 
</P>
<P>
In the past year, Eastern Europe has begun moving toward free market systems. 
That won't help American farmers, but it may be a windfall for food processors, 
one analyst said. 
</P>
<P>
Richard Judy, a Soviet specialist at the Hudson Institute, said there will be a 
demand for companies involved in food processing and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
One of them is Central Soya, based in Ft. Wayne, Ind. Since January, it has 
formed joint ventures with Hungary's state-owned agribusiness concern to 
produce livestock feed and with a Yugoslav company to produce soybean 
concentrates used in meat processing. 
</P>
<P>
Bioprocessing represents another opportunity. Genetically engineered 
microorganisms will be used to produce food, fuel, industrial feedstocks and 
commodity chemicals from corn, sugar cane and other crops, said John R. 
Campbell, president of Oklahoma State University. 
</P>
<P>
However, such products may meet with resistance, including consumer fears. 
</P>
<P>
"Technology has been one of the major reasons for the success in American 
agriculture," said John Urbanchek, senior vice president for economics in the 
Washington office of consulting firm Hill and Knowlton Inc. 
</P>
<P>
"The problem is that the contribution of current technology is being rapidly 
exhausted and must be replaced if the United States is to retain its prominence 
as an agricultural producer and exporter, and to continue to supply American 
consumers with high-quality, safe and reasonably priced food," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- AGRICULTURE; TECHNOLOGY; FOOD; TRENDS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080590-0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257931 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 5, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 2; Column 2; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
790 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER NOTEBOOK: TAKING THE MYSTERY OUT OF LISTING TERMS; 
</P>
<P>
HOME SALES: THERE ARE SEVERAL CHOICES FOR THE HOMEOWNER WHEN CONTRACTING WITH A 
REAL ESTATE AGENT TO SELL PROPERTY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT J. BRUSS, Bruss is a San Francisco-based syndicated real estate 
columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If you are thinking of selling your home, it will pay to spend a few minutes 
considering the pros and cons of your listing choices. 
</P>
<P>
To a real estate agent, a property listing is inventory. It costs the agent 
nothing. But a fairly priced listing gives the agent control of an asset that, 
if the agent does his or her job well, should produce a handsome sales 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
A listing is a contract between the real estate owner and a realty agent 
whereby the seller agrees to pay the agent a fee for selling the property on 
acceptable terms. But there are several types of listings, with different legal 
consequences, for the seller and agent. 
</P>
<P>
1 -- Open listings. From a real estate agent's viewpoint, the worst type of 
listing is the open listing. It is a written or oral invitation by a property 
owner to one or more real estate agents to find a buyer on terms acceptable to 
the seller. The first agent to bring a purchase contract, which the seller 
accepts, earns the entire sales commission. 
</P>
<P>
But an open listing is really no listing. At first glance, the open listing 
might seem attractive to agents. However, if the owner finds a buyer without an 
agent's help, then the seller owes no sales commission. Or the property owner 
can withdraw the property from the market and owe no fee to an agent. 
</P>
<P>
Because of this lack of control over the sale, most realty agents will work on 
open listings only if the potential commission is large and there is nothing 
else to do on a rainy day. Few agents will advertise or spend much time on open 
listings. 
</P>
<P>
2 -- Exclusive listings. An exclusive listing means the owner has listed the 
property for sale with just one real estate agent. However, there are two types 
of exclusive listings: 
</P>
<P>
Exclusive right to sell. Regardless of who finds a buyer for the property, 
whether it is the seller, the listing agent or a selling agent, the listing 
agent will earn the sales commission. Of course, if two agents are involved in 
the sale, they split the sales fee. 
</P>
<P>
Most realty agents prefer this type of listing, because it gives the agent 
maximum control over the sale. For this reason, agents gladly invest their time 
and money in the sale of a property listed on an exclusive right to sell. 
</P>
<P>
Most real estate agents don't want property owners to know about an exclusive 
agency listing. It earns the exclusive agent a sales commission if the listing 
agent, or any other licensee, finds an acceptable buyer for the property. 
</P>
<P>
However, if the property owner finds a buyer without the help of a licensed 
real estate agent, then the listing agent does not earn a sales commission. In 
other words, this type of listing creates a race between the owner and the 
exclusive agent to find a buyer. 
</P>
<P>
3 -- Multiple listings. This is not really a type of listing. A multiple 
listing is either an exclusive right to sell, or an exclusive agency listing, 
which is submitted to the local multiple listing service (MLS) for distribution 
to all member real estate brokers. 
</P>
<P>
The MLS is a cooperative organization, often run by the local Board of 
Realtors, for sharing listings to give them the widest possible market exposure 
to agents who may have buyers looking for the exclusively listed property. 
</P>
<P>
The MLS does not accept open listings from the general public. Computers are 
widely used by local MLS members to quickly distribute the listings to members 
who also usually receive weekly MLS books with photos of all current listings. 
The MLS is considered a major marketing tool by agents and their sellers. 
</P>
<P>
4 -- Net listings. A dangerous variation of an exclusive listing is the net 
listing, where the property owner specifies the net amount desired for the 
property and any amount received above this minimum becomes the agent's 
commission. Net listings are illegal in some states, but are legal in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
To illustrate, suppose you sign a $100,000 net listing for your property. If 
your realty agent obtains a $120,000 offer, you will feel cheated and might 
refuse to accept unless the agent cuts his $20,000 commission. However, if the 
agent receives a $100,000 purchase offer, the agent will earn nothing and might 
be tempted to forget to deliver such a low offer to you. The best way to avoid 
these net listing pitfalls is to exclusively list your property for sale at its 
fair market value, based on recent sales prices of nearby comparable 
properties. 
</P>
<P>
By knowing your real estate listing alternatives, you can decide which type of 
listing is best for you. For most home sellers the exclusive right to sell 
listing is best, because it gives the realty agent maximum sales incentive. 
Such a listing should be submitted by the agent to the local multiple listing 
service for maximum market exposure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080590-0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 257932 </DOCID>
